headline: Beef cattle producers meeting to be held in Nevada on Dec. 11; Preregister by Dec. 5 - Bolivar Herald Free-Press
body_text: Wednesday, November 26, 2025 39 ° Clear Forecast Log in Beef cattle producers meeting to be held in Nevada on Dec. 11; Preregister by Dec. 5 “Understanding markets as well as suggestions on feeding cattle through the winter are important for a cattle operation to function properly,” says Patrick Davis, MU Extension Livestock Field Specialist. Furthermore, understanding financial tools that are available to cattle producers is helpful in planning for operational success in the future. Therefore, MU Extension is partnering with FCS Financial to provide a cattle producers meeting to cover these topics on Dec. 11 at 6 p.m. at the Vernon County Fairgrounds Centennial Hall at 1641 E Ashland Street, Nevada. headline: Thanksgiving Holiday Safety - Bolivar Herald Free-Press
body_text: Wednesday, November 26, 2025 34 ° Clear Forecast Log in Thanksgiving Holiday Safety Colonel Michael A. Turner, superintendent of the Missouri State Highway Patrol, reminds everyone there will be an increase in traffic over the Thanksgiving holiday. The Thanksgiving holiday is one of the busiest travel periods of the year, with Wednesday and Sunday afternoon/evenings being the most heavily traveled times. Drivers should expect more traffic and the possibility of delays throughout the weekend. Regardless of traffic patterns, safety should remain a priority. Coach Kyle Gawlowski says, "We put up a valiant fight in front of a packed home crowd for Courtwarming but fell just short to rival Fair Grove, 65-54. headline: It's beginning to look a lot like Christmas on the Ozark Square
body_text:
On the heels of the recent Halloween Trunk or Treat, the Ozark downtown square is giving off a holiday vibe. City workers recently set up the square's traditional Christmas decorations, and 28 students from Ozark High School painted the windows of the buildings along the square with cheerful, holiday scenes. And for those who are in the mood to help the less fortunate enjoy the holidays, drop-off boxes for toys, coats, and canned food items can be found on the east side of the square. Also, be sure to be at the square to catch the 60th annual Ozark Chamber Christmas Parade on Saturday, Nov. 22, and Friday Night Lights on Friday, Dec. 12.

In the week leading up to Halloween, the Nixa X-Center held its Halloween Spooktacular on Friday, Oct. 24, while the Ozark Community Center held its Frightfest the next evening. Both events, which included Halloween games, activities, and of course, lots of candy, easily saw attendances of over 2,000 people.

Gary Arlee Brown, 77, passed away on Saturday, Oct. 25, 2025, after an extended illness. Born in rural Arkansas, he moved to Southwest Missouri at age three and became a life-long resident of Northern Stone and Christian Counties. Gary was a man of many talents, careers, and connections. If you needed something, he probably had it to sell to you; if you needed something done, he had a guy. If you lived in Christian, Stone, or Barry Counties, chances are you had met Gary at least once. He did everything from probate auctions to owning car washes and convenience stores to real estate. But his real passion was livestock markets. He was an avid coon hunter in his younger years and became a solid fisherman in retirement.

headline: “I’ll Be Home for Christmas” performs at Stained Glass Theatre in Ozark
body_text:
Set in late 1941, “I’ll Be Home for Christmas” is the story of the faith of a family and a nation on the brink of World War II, preparing to celebrate the birth of the Prince of Peace. The music highlights the sounds of the ‘40s, including swing, lush ballads, and big band songs, interspersed with reenactments of radio broadcasts during that time. Original music mixed with familiar Christmas favorites forms the backdrop for this memorable, dramatic musical. Written by Deborah Craig-Claar; music by Mark Hayes.

headline: Vet clinic receives threat, insults over misattributed social media post
body_text:
On Wednesday, Sept. 10, the conservative political activist Charlie Kirk was killed by an assassin’s bullet while speaking at Utah Valley University in Orem, Utah. Not long afterwards, Dr. Chris Rispoli, co-owner of the Gentle Care Animal Hospital in Edmond, Okla., made a social media post disparaging Kirk and suggesting that other people like him would also be killed. Several people reacted angrily to Rispoli’s post. However, some of those responding to Rispoli directed their anger at the Gentle Care Animal Hospital in Nixa, a veterinary clinic that has the same name as Rispoli’s but is not affiliated with them.

headline: There is no greater gift than Jesus
body_text:
This item is available in full to subscribers.

Attention subscribers





If the system cannot find your info, please call us at 573-564-2339 or email standardnews@socket.net.



Otherwise, click here to view your options for subscribing.

Please log in to continue

E-mail Password

Log in

Dear editor,

As we approach Thanksgiving Day on November 27, let us remember that first Thanksgiving Day when the Pilgrims and Indians came together to enjoy a great Thanksgiving feast. The winter before had been so hard on the pilgrims, with many of them not even surviving. Even so, with a plentiful harvest that year, the survivors were rejoicing with the Indians and thanking God for their blessings.

As we enjoy our Thanksgiving dinner with family and friends, let us remember to thank God for our many blessings. Most of all, let us be thankful for Jesus Christ, the Son of God, who left His home in heaven to come to earth to live among His creation. Jesus loves us so much that He was willing to become the sacrifice on the cross of Calvary so that His blood could cover our sins. When we give our lives to Jesus in obedience to His will, our sins will be forgiven and we will have the promise of living in heaven with Him for all of eternity. There is no greater gift. Thank you Jesus.

JM Stock

High Hill

headline: New weight restrictions placed on three bridges in Montgomery County
body_text:
Signs indicating a weight limit changes for three bridges in Montgomery County have been installed at the following locations:

Route K over the Loutre River: 20 tons for single-unit vehicles and 35 tons for combination tractor-trailers. This bridge, built in 1960, is scheduled to be replaced next year.

headline: JBE Optimist Student of the Month
body_text:
Parker Calbreath was named the recipient of the Jonesburg Elementary 5th Grade Optimist Student of the Month of September. The Jonesburg Optimist Club sponsors the Jonesburg Elementary 5th Grade Optimist Student of the Month. In order to receive this award, students make their classmates feel that there is something special about them, they look for the positive or sunny side of everything to make their optimism come true and they forget about the mistakes of the past and press on to the greater achievements of the future. Each student of the month receives a plaque presented by the Optimist Club.

headline: Senior of the Month: Harry Johnson
body_text:
Harry Johnson comes to the Montgomery County Senior Center on Wednesday mornings with some other wonderful seniors who play great music for the citizens to listen to. Harry and his wonderful wife hold the JAM music sections during the summer at the center. Harry helps out with so many things and has a wonderful upbeat personality for all of the people to smile about. He helps out with the upkeep of the pool tables, pool sticks and so much more. He enjoys playing pool and having a good time with fellowship at the center. Thanks to Harry for all of his help and fun times at the center.

headline: Backward glance for Nov. 28
body_text:
This week's Backward Glance begins with an ad for a Thanksgiving special at an affordable rate from a local Warrensburg cafe in 1908, moves on to a series of notices about folks coming home for the holidays in the 1930s, then outlines a school Thanksgiving holiday program and all those who performed in it back in 1940, and then wraps up with news of eight lucky prisoners in the county jail who were treated to a full Thanksgiving feast back in 1958.

headline: Statewide winter weather drill set for Oct. 16
body_text:
JEFFERSON CITY – With winter weather just around the corner, the Missouri Department of Transportation will hold its annual winter operations drill on Thursday, Oct. 16. Motorists may notice an increased number of MoDOT vehicles on state routes during the drill, which will begin at 8 a.m. in rural areas and 9 a.m. in urban areas. The exercise should be completed by 3 p.m. With turnover rates and many positions still open, driver training on this day is more critical than ever.

headline: Backward Glance for Nov. 7
body_text:
This week's Backward Glance begins with news of a one-man band local to Warrensburg in 1919, then outlines a series of advertisements for local Pie Suppers from that same year. The glance back then covers news of a local Shakespeare Club in 1951, and highlights a local senior from Holden in the same year, and then concludes with news of a local Chilhowee tavern having its liquor license revoked in the early 1960s.

headline: The woman with the vacuum
body_text:
Shortly after my first cancer diagnosis in 2017, I contacted a peer mentor program for synovial sarcoma, my kind of cancer. I was matched with a woman from Kansas who had been a patient for several years, and I called her to ask her advice for dealing with the mental hardships of our aggressive disease. When she answered the phone, I asked her how she was doing.

headline: State Fair Speedway Donates $1,000 to Retrieving Freedom, Inc.
body_text:
The roar of engines and the spirit of community came together once again as the historic State Fair Speedway celebrated its 9th consecutive year of racing for a cause. With more than 3,500 fans filling the stands, organizers Larry McCown and Randy Combs were proud to dedicate the 2025 race to the memory of Barbara Hayden, honoring her years of support for the Missouri State Fair and her unwavering dedication to preserving the legacy of Sedalia dirt track racing.

headline: Finding gratitude in the everyday
body_text:
Every Thanksgiving, after the farm chores are done, the turkey is consumed and the football games have been both played and watched, I bask in the silence for just a few moments. In years past, I’ve written here about how grateful I am for the family, friends and colleagues who play such a huge role in my life. I’ve noted how blessed we have been to work in agriculture despite the ups and downs. I’ve shared how excited I am about the weeks to come with our Missouri Farm Bureau annual meeting and the holiday season that comes with the turn of the calendar.

headline: A Dinosaur Goes to the Library
body_text:
I’m not even 40 years old, but I’m already an old lady. I can feel it in my bones and in my soul. The new world is a strange and unfamiliar place, and to be honest, I don’t like it. It’s fast, it’s rude, but most of all, it’s just too darn loud. Now, I know some things are meant to be loud: rock concerts, demolition, crying babies, football games. I enjoy that kind of loud. A place for everything and everything in its place, right? What I can’t get used to is the steady march of noise into places that used to be sanctuaries of silence.

headline: Sedalia Democrat
body_text:
I never did like Rush Limbaugh. I didn’t like his bombastic belligerence, his pugilistic and confrontational invective, his bellicose blathering. This is all before stating the obvious: I didn’t like what he said. I didn’t like that he dismissed those whose opinions differed from his in the slightest. I didn’t like his continual fostering of anger. I didn’t like that he was plain mean.

body_text:

The Liberty Christian girls basketball team needed a win in the worst way on Tuesday.

Coming off back-to-back losses, Liberty faced an Eagle Ridge Christian team from Cape Girardeau and managed to right the ship in the 43-34 home win.

Freshman guard Bristol Barron, who led the Eagles (3-2) in scoring with 15 points, praised the team for jumping to leads of 16-4 after the first quarter and 21-12 by halftime.

“This feels really good, I knew we had it in us,” Barron said. “We had to keep putting that hustle and that drive in.”

Liberty coach Kim Meyer said that the team was able to wear down the opposition by using a pair of groups that shifted in and out of the game at regular intervals to keep the team fresh.

“I thought they worked really well together tonight,” Meyer said. “We’re still learning as a team and growing. The girls are developing a good unity. They’re doing very well, encouraging one another.”

After Barron, junior Mallory Boenker added seven points and senior Trina Scheltens pitched in five.

Having returned to winning ways, Liberty will now head to Calvary Lutheran in Jefferson City for a game on Monday. The opening tip is scheduled for 6 p.m.

Officials with the Wright City Fire Protection District said the cause of a fire that started in a garage of a home on Beretta Court is still under investigation.

A fire Saturday at a home on Beretta Court in Wright City was contained and crews were able to save 50 percent of the home according to an official with the Wright City Fire Protection District.

Assistant Chief Josh Riebe said the call of a fire in a garage in a home on Beretta Court came in around 4:25 p.m. Saturday afternoon. Riebe said that when firefighters arrived on scene there was fire clearly visible on the roof above the garage. He said everyone was able to exit the home safely, including the family dog.

Riebe said crews worked to contain the fire and were able to stop the fire from getting into the portion of the home where the bedrooms are located.

In addition to Wright City fire personnel, Riebe said his department was assisted by the Warrenton Fire Protection District and Wentzville Fire Protection District. Riebe said the Wright City Police Department also assisted with traffic management on Wildcat Drive and the Warren County Ambulance District was on standby.

News

Trained noses on call

When disasters occur across Missouri or within the United States, Missouri Task Force 1 (MOTF-1) is trained and ready to respond. It is one of 28 urban search and rescue teams in the nation and is managed by Boone County Fire Protection District in Columbia. A unique team from Marthasville is on rotation to respond, but instead of using the typical rescue skills, two of its members use their highly sophisticated noses. Glenda Eichmeyer and two of her dogs, Athena, and Lily, are certified members of MOTF-1.

Once again, the Fayette Advertiser will deliver letters to Santa to the North Pole.

Santa and Mrs. Claus are lifelong subscribers to this newspaper. We take great pride in printing letters addressed to him at the North Pole so that he and Mrs. Claus may double-check those Christmas lists.

Be sure and drop off letters to the newspaper office at 203. N. Main St. in Fayette. Drop them through our mail slot after hours or place them in Santa’s Mailbox at the Fayette Post Office, Peacock Beauty Shop, or the Downtown Fayette office on South Main Street.

They may also be mailed to the newspaper office at PO Box 32 or emailed to news@fayettenews.com.

The deadline to have your letter printed is 5 p.m. on Friday, Dec. 19. Our last edition before Christmas publishes on Dec. 24.

The final event of the calendar year at the Ashby-Hodge Gallery of American Art will be open on Monday, Dec. 1, with the annual Christmas sale and show set to run through December 11 on the campus of Central Methodist University.

Each year during the holiday season, the Gallery opens its doors to the public for a sale of works donated specifically to be sold. This year’s sale features a range of paintings, drawings, posters, and other works. A special collection of drama works will be available for purchase alongside the art.

The other half of this annual event is the student art show, featuring the works of students in the fall semester design class taught by Tyler Pierson and the works of students in the photography class taught by Jill Barringhaus.

The show and sale will run from Dec. 1-11, with the Gallery open from 1:30 to 4:30 p.m. on Sunday, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday. Special tours and groups are welcome by contacting Pierson at 660-248-6304 or tpierson@centralmethodist.edu.

Fayette High School has a bright new digital sign at its entrance along Highway 5. Commercial Trust Company of Fayette donated $50,000 to help the district replace the old sign. Alexander and Associates installed the new sign on October 2.

“It’s an honor for Commercial Trust to partner with the Fayette R-III Schools in many ways over the years,” said Commercial Trust Co. President Janet Jacobs, herself a Fayette High School graduate. “The school is the heart of our community, and Commercial Trust is proud to show our Falcon pride with the sponsorship of this new sign. We hope everyone who drives by will take pride in our schools and the students, teachers, staff, administration, and parents who all represent Fayette in a positive way throughout our area.”

The new sign features a large digital display that shows the date and time, weather information, positive student messages, a weekly events schedule, and employment opportunities.

The old sign was installed in August 2007 at the request of then Commercial Trust President Jay Jacobs, who, along with his wife, Kelly, donated $500,000 to the school in April of that year.

A 41-year-old New Franklin man was killed late Friday night in a single-vehicle crash on Route P north of County Road 451 in Howard County.

According to a Missouri State Highway Patrol crash report, the accident occurred at approximately 10 p.m. on Friday, September 12. The patrol reports that a 2005 Arctic Cat ATV traveled off the right side of the roadway, overturned, and ejected the driver.

The driver, whose name had not been released at press time, was pronounced dead at the scene by Howard County Coroner Trisha Clark at 7:50 a.m. on September 13.

The ATV sustained minor damage and was towed from the scene. The driver was not wearing a safety device, according to the patrol.

This crash marks Troop F’s first fatality for September and the 29th fatality of 2025, according to the Highway Patrol.
